<br>
This game snuck out with no hype whatsoever, in fact its only being sold by Electronics Boutique.  The game is surprisingly good, i played it most of the weekend, and it reminds me alot of a single player mmorpg-style game.  Its first person perspective and they've created a large world to explore.  The interface is unique, and although i didnt like it in the beginning, i've grown to like it after a few hours of using it.  The graphics arent great, but they arent bad either.  Wizardry games all combine technology with magic, so its abit like Arcanum i guess.  The character customizing as far as stats and skills go has a lot of depth.  You can play a ton of races(wolf-like or Half-dragon, etc.) as well as have alot of classes to choose from(Samurai, Ninja, Gadgeteer, Mage, Bard, etc).  You also specialize in certain areas very similar to DAOC skills, and with some classes like a mage, you can cast spells then choose the power at which you'd like to cast.  <br>
<br>
Overall, its a good game, in fact surprisingly very good.  There seems to be abit of hype on the game that i read, since Gamespot recently came out with a flattering review.  Its not the greatest rpg, and going to some of the forums, some of the hype is overrated imo, but it deserves most of it since it came out so low-key.  I'm pretty sure i remember seeing a full shelf of Wizardry 8 the same day i went and picked up DAOC, so its been out for awhile now.  The developers of the game did a great job imo, since i havent experienced any bugs, the world is vast and complex, and the graphics arent bad considering they have never done a 3d game like this before.  As for me saying its like a single-player mmorpg, i think you'll see some similarities when you play it.  It at least reminds me of more like an mmorpg than any other single player rpg i've played.  <br>
<br>
If you can handle a mix between magic and technology(i.e. guns and spells), kinda slow combat, and alot of customizing with your skills and abilities, then i think you'll like Wizardry 8.  I played Wizardry 7 and i think one before that, but they arent even comparable to Wizardry 8.  If you have any questions about it, just ask.  I really like this game, and it deserves more hype.  Its kinda sad that this is supposed to be the last Wizardry due to problems with the company i think, as well as problems with release of thsi game.  I know they intended to continue the series originally since this was their first foray into 3D which turned out great.  They did a great job, and its sad how this game deserve more hype than most rpg's that i've purchased recently but its not getting any.  We'll see how good player word of mouth is, and reviews from places like Gamespot. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ucolcannon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Colcannon</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(12/4/01 12:00:16 pm)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sleeper Single-player RPG of the year....</span><hr size=1> I totally loved this game :) Very old school and very fun. This is what Ultima IX shoulda been. The fact you can import characters from you previous games is a novelty that doesn't seem to be done quite so often anymore.<br>
<br>
The new class Gadgeteer is really cool and pretty innovative. It's a kind of rogue class that tinkers on the side. You can create items that possess spells (Forcefield Generator = Armour buff) with unlimited charges -- although you pay with stamina instead of Magic points. They can also upgrade their custom weapon - the Omnigun - at various points  to allow different abilities (kill, blind, etc) as well as changing ammo (arrows, darts, etc)<br>
<br>
The game play is VERY addictive as well as being very hard. You have to use strategy to plan out  your encounters and know when it's best to run. <br>
<br>
I highly recommend this to folks who - like me - cut their RPG teeth of games such as Ultima and Wizardry<br>
<br>
Edit: Also, you can go into the options screen an change the combat speed as well as the movement of monsters during their battle turns. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ucolcannon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Colcannon</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0> at: 12/4/01 12:02:58 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukhieran.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Khieran</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(12/10/01 6:14:36 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sleeper Single-player RPG of the year....</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt;&gt;it reminds me alot of a single player mmorpg-style game&lt;&lt;&lt;<br>
